<br>
Think about it, the class balance has shifted back and forth and back and forth.  Mobs were given new abilities, with no clear line of thinking about why a mob would be able to summon a player character into melee range of them for example.  Haste items went from being a rare type of item to being fairly common.  Focus items were there for some classes, but not others.  There's no way to really make the level of items that drop from many mobs as well.<br>
<br>
So, what Artifact Entertainment did with Horizons was to start off with a game world, with different races, a history, how the races interact, and make the physics of the world very clearly defined.  THEN they began to work on coding the game around 2 years or so ago.  It's gone through changes in that time, obviously.  One nice thing about having an idea about what you are doing before you start doing it is you can plan out how to make the product work.  The UI, and how you view the world, graphics, and so on can actually be implemented later in the process, which is why we will see the graphics done using pixel shaders.<br>
<br>
  The more advanced your video card is, the more advanced the pixel shader routines can be in the code.  Pixel shader versions 1.1 and 1.4 will be available to MOST people, but shader version 2.0 will require that you have at least a Radeon 9500 or Geforce FX.  Cards based on ATI and Nvidia that came out before these mentioned cards did not have the hardware support for pixel shader 2.0.  BUT, Horizons is being written so that it will use the best shader version for YOUR equipment.  This means the game will look the best on the latest video cards, but you won't be disappointed in the graphics.  I've heard that some people were disappointed with the demonstration at E3 this year.  From what I heard though, the game was being shown on a Geforce 4 MX card, so we will have to wait to see how good the graphics will be.<br>
<br>
One thing I know is that EQ may have a lot of back story, but there's so little information given to the players, either in game or even on the web site, that we have to make up our own stories about why, when you kill something in Mistmoore, that it gives a +Ring of Scale faction hit.  If there were in-game events, nothing of it made it onto an obvious place on the EQ web pages.  With Horizons, I have more faith that the world won't just dump you in a newbie area with nothing more than a note to give to a NPC that doesn't even tell you what's going on in the game world.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
